00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:54.439
So I have in front of you here the different deployment modes.

00:00:54.439 --> 00:01:02.279
And this is essentially, if we were to take the deployment modes from the Apache website,

00:01:03.240 --> 00:01:05.160
the official Spark website here.

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:13.320
So if I can go here, and I go deploying, you'll notice that it says standalone, mesos, and yarn.

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:14.199
So you have these three.

00:01:15.239 --> 00:01:16.279
These match right here.

00:01:17.239 --> 00:01:24.279
You know, mesos, which is just a symbol for mesos and yarn, and then the standalone cluster.

00:01:24.279 --> 00:01:31.480
So these are the two sections right here that cover the ones that Spark is talking about.

00:01:32.519 --> 00:01:38.279
And then we have the deployments based on the articles from our website,

00:01:38.279 --> 00:01:42.440
which talks about local and cluster, right?

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:48.199
So this diagram here is meant to show basically the two together, right?

00:01:48.839 --> 00:01:55.480
How can we work with Spark VR and Spark in both of the deployment modes?

00:01:56.599 --> 00:02:00.360
So the first one is talking about a managed cluster, right?

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:05.559
It's either managed through yarn, which is the most common, and then managed through mesos.

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:13.160
Usually, whenever you have a managed cluster, that means that the resources are being managed

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:22.440
centrally, and that you have a master node and then some slave nodes in the cluster.

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:28.440
Whenever we talk about adding R and Spark VR to the cluster,

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:34.600
it usually means that we're going to add it to one of the nodes, usually like an edge node, right?

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:38.600
So you don't have to have R in every single package installed in every single node.

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:47.399
That's one of the big advantages I feel of Spark VR is because it's a very great approach,

00:02:47.399 --> 00:02:49.399
which I talked about in the first webinar.

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:57.000
And simple approach allows it to not have to be running in every single node.

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:00.039
Same thing for standalone cluster.

00:03:00.919 --> 00:03:07.240
You'll notice that it's not a managed network, and that means that there's not a service

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:09.240
that coordinates everything.

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:14.039
What it is, is there's an actual machine that's called the master node

00:03:14.039 --> 00:03:15.960
that is the one that coordinates all the work.

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:23.479
So usually, you can install the R and Spark VR in one of the other nodes,

00:03:24.199 --> 00:03:28.199
but also you can install in the master node, and I've done that both ways.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.720
I usually end up putting the master node myself,

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:37.720
just because the master node doesn't give any resources once you open a new Spark connection.

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:43.240
This standalone cluster is actually really useful whenever you want to

00:03:44.039 --> 00:03:48.520
basically get your feet wet with an actual Spark implementation.

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:55.000
If you want to try it out and you don't want to build an entire data lake,

