Spark Apply function.

00:08:56.359 --> 00:08:58.840
This does change the paradigm a little bit,

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:01.080
where we usually say, like I was saying here,

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:03.239
you don't need to install R in every single node.

00:09:04.119 --> 00:09:07.320
In this case, you would if you want to do Spark Apply.

00:09:08.119 --> 00:09:11.960
So you don't have to have every library installed.

00:09:11.960 --> 00:09:15.559
That's something that the Spark Apply command will help you do.

00:09:15.559 --> 00:09:19.640
But you do need to have R in the nodes that you're running against.

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:25.799
So this is another consideration that I think needs to be said,

00:09:25.799 --> 00:09:29.960
that you don't have to have R in every single node

00:09:29.960 --> 00:09:31.479
if you're not going to use Spark Apply.

00:09:31.479 --> 00:09:34.359
But if you do, that changes the architecture a little bit.

00:09:34.919 --> 00:09:43.080
If you're a data scientist that is trying to find the easiest way

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:46.039
to move your R code into and scale it up,

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:52.039
this may be a good way, at least it looks at first.

00:09:52.039 --> 00:09:56.520
But just know that the code that you're running in here

00:09:56.520 --> 00:09:58.840
would have to be highly parallelized.

00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:02.039
So a good way of thinking about this is,

00:10:02.440 --> 00:10:06.359
if I have a, let's say, a model that I want to run,

00:10:07.239 --> 00:10:10.919
or I want to fit against all the customers in my database, right?

00:10:10.919 --> 00:10:12.919
So I want to run a linear regression,

00:10:12.919 --> 00:10:16.520
a single linear regression against each individual customer.

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:20.280
Then this model may work really well for you,

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:24.599
because what it's doing is that it's going to take each of those customers,

00:10:24.599 --> 00:10:27.960
it's going to run the model in each worker node,

00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:30.119
and so it's going to separate the job that way.

00:10:30.200 --> 00:10:34.520
But let's say now, if I were to have a really large job,

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:38.679
let's say I want to run the same model over all my customer activity,

00:10:38.679 --> 00:10:40.520
regardless of who the customer are,

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:42.760
then there's not a good way of parallelizing it,

00:10:42.760 --> 00:10:47.239
and that's where that may not be the best choice to do the Spark Apply,

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:52.679
or at least this way, it may be better to consider

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:57.960
a native Spark machine learning library,

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:03.080
or maybe an extension, like a H2O extension, for example.

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:07.000
So I just want to mention that as you start using Spark Apply

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:08.599
and getting acquainted with it,

00:11:08.599 --> 00:11:13.719
that that would be a good way of kind of knowing if you can switch or not.

