00:12:08.359 --> 00:12:10.760
So real quick, Spark concepts.

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:15.479
So we have a driver, a master, a worker, and an executor.

00:12:15.479 --> 00:12:20.520
So just to clarify, sometimes the executor

00:12:21.479 --> 00:12:27.080
and the, when we say executor, it gets confused with a worker,

00:12:28.520 --> 00:12:32.919
or sometimes we hear the term of driver,

00:12:32.919 --> 00:12:35.239
and it's kind of hard to separate all of them

00:12:35.239 --> 00:12:37.320
because it's not the same terms that we use in group.

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:44.039
So a driver is essentially the program that starts the Spark context.

00:12:45.239 --> 00:12:48.039
So that would be Spark VR in our case, right?

00:12:48.039 --> 00:12:52.200
And usually the machine or the server that starts that program

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:53.640
is considered a driver node.

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:57.479
Then the master would be, you know,

00:12:57.479 --> 00:12:59.559
whomever is managing the Spark job,

00:12:59.559 --> 00:13:01.239
which is, it could be like I mentioned,

00:13:01.239 --> 00:13:05.479
either a machine itself, a server, or a service, right?

00:13:05.479 --> 00:13:06.280
Like Yarn.

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:09.640
And then a worker is essentially the machines

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:12.359
where you're going to actually do the heavy lifting, right?

00:13:12.359 --> 00:13:14.280
It's going to do the calculations.

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:16.919
But where it gets tricky is the fact that

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.880
each worker will not handle only one job.

00:13:21.880 --> 00:13:26.760
You can actually have multiple jobs running inside the same worker

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:33.719
because how Spark works is that splits the work amongst executors.

00:13:33.719 --> 00:13:38.039
So you can technically have more than one executor inside a worker.

00:13:38.039 --> 00:13:41.320
And that is very important to know and to keep in mind

00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:45.320
because that goes back to how we do those deployments.

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:50.599
And when I say deployment, I'm actually also using a higher term,

00:13:50.599 --> 00:13:53.719
which is not only deploying a new environment,

00:13:53.719 --> 00:14:02.679
but also deploying analysis and deploying a new connection to Spark.

00:14:04.119 --> 00:14:07.239
Another thing that is important to keep in mind

00:14:07.239 --> 00:14:11.479
is how we do data load with Spark VR.

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:16.840
So at the end of the day, it boils down to two options that we have.

00:14:17.640 --> 00:14:22.440
The first option is to essentially tell Spark VR where the data is, right?

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:27.559
So we tell Spark, hey, the data is in this high table.

00:14:27.559 --> 00:14:29.640
Go ahead and cache it, right?

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:34.119
So when it caches it, it never goes through my R environment.

00:14:34.119 --> 00:14:36.359
It goes directly into the Spark cluster.

00:14:36.359 --> 00:14:39.559
And then I can use Spark VR to see the data in there.

00:14:40.359 --> 00:14:44.200
I can also tell, hey, my data is in this S3 bucket.

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:44.760
Go get it.

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:50.919
Then Spark can go and get it through a Spark package

00:14:50.919 --> 00:14:54.039
to be able to know how to read the S3 data and bring the data in.

00:14:54.039 --> 00:14:56.039
Again, it doesn't go through R.

00:14:56.039 --> 00:15:04.919
So this is the best approach to have when we are using Spark to bring large data sets

00:15:05.479 --> 00:15:15.000
because what we found is that a lot of new users will try to do option two right off the bat,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.640
which is you can notice that the data is first.

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:27.640
So in this case, you have a bunch of data that we load into our environment

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:29.880
and then try to push that into the cluster.

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:32.119
This works really good.

00:15:32.119 --> 00:15:33.799
In fact, we're going to see that today.

00:15:33.799 --> 00:15:37.239
But for smaller data sets, usually you want this option two.

00:15:38.679 --> 00:15:48.200
You will need to use it for lookup tables to enrich the data of the main data set

00:15:48.200 --> 00:15:49.400
that you already have in Spark.

00:15:50.119 --> 00:15:56.440
This option two should be the last option that you should take.

00:15:57.239 --> 00:16:01.239
Option one should be always the first thing that you want to look at.

00:16:01.239 --> 00:16:08.039
You want to make sure that Spark ingests the data, not that R ingests the data.

00:16:09.159 --> 00:16:15.559
This, like I said, not knocking down option two because it's very useful, like I said,

00:16:15.559 --> 00:16:19.479
to bring in more information, more meta information about your data,

00:16:19.479 --> 00:16:21.320
but shouldn't be your first choice.

00:16:22.840 --> 00:16:24.679
Two things that Spark needs to read the data.

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:27.239
Obviously, access to the data.

00:16:27.960 --> 00:16:29.479
And the second is a parser.

00:16:29.960 --> 00:16:37.000
So it needs to know how to read Redshift databases, how to read CSV files,

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:41.000
how to read Hive data, how to read S3 buckets.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:47.080
So all that different parsers are usually handled via a package.

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:53.640
And when I say access to data, I'm going to switch back to this one right here.

00:16:53.640 --> 00:16:57.239
So when I say access to data, it means that every node in that cluster

00:16:57.239 --> 00:16:59.000
needs access to that data.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:03.559
This means, and which is kind of tricky because sometimes we may have a file

00:17:03.559 --> 00:17:09.239
that we bring into this node, but these two nodes cannot see the file, right?

00:17:09.239 --> 00:17:13.719
So when we try to load it into memory, it won't work because they don't have the same path

00:17:13.719 --> 00:17:20.040
to the file I have in the file introduced or uploaded to the one node.

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:24.839
So that's why I mentioned here that for standalone mode,

00:17:24.839 --> 00:17:29.319
especially, a simple approach is to create a network share.

00:17:29.319 --> 00:17:37.560
So if you want to do a simple file that you want to have Spark read into memory

00:17:38.119 --> 00:17:41.640
without having to have an S3 bucket or if you don't have a data lake,

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:44.199
then just use a simple network share.

00:17:44.199 --> 00:17:52.359
And I've done that, the Samba share, it makes the same path, relative path,

00:17:52.359 --> 00:17:56.599
the same amongst all the nodes in the cluster and you're able to ingest your data.

