physical details, you know, so AWS is not really physical, but it's four worker nodes,

00:19:20.599 --> 00:19:23.560
they have 15 gigabytes of RAM, each have four cores.

00:19:23.560 --> 00:19:27.640
So obviously, we have a total of 16 cores, 60 gigs of RAM available.

00:19:27.640 --> 00:19:29.079
It's just a very small cluster.

00:19:29.640 --> 00:19:33.640
But hopefully, you'll see some of the examples here and how that would apply to your cluster.

00:19:35.880 --> 00:19:38.040
There's two, three settings here.

00:19:38.040 --> 00:19:41.800
The two main ones are Yarn and Node Manager.

00:19:42.439 --> 00:19:47.079
We have Resource Memory and Resource CPU vCores.

00:19:47.959 --> 00:19:54.599
These are the two that may need to be updated in your manager, you know, whatever

00:19:55.560 --> 00:19:58.359
system you use to manage in this case, for their manager,

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:04.280
you can make those changes in the actual setup.

00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:08.119
So this may be something that you need to work with your

00:20:08.920 --> 00:20:11.560
big data administrator.

00:20:12.119 --> 00:20:17.079
And I talked about that in that article here, the deployment connections article

00:20:18.359 --> 00:20:20.520
that's mentioned here.

00:20:24.040 --> 00:20:30.920
Because usually, there's an error that occurs that the default is set pretty low,

00:20:31.640 --> 00:20:33.800
like eight gigabytes per executor.

00:20:33.800 --> 00:20:37.079
So if you ask for nine gigabytes, you'll see this error.

00:20:37.079 --> 00:20:43.000
And it tells you right there to go look at those settings.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:48.680
And these settings cannot be set in the configuration like we do here.

00:20:49.479 --> 00:20:57.800
Those settings can only be changed in the manager here or directly in the XML file for Yarn.

00:20:58.680 --> 00:21:00.920
So that's something very important to keep in mind.

00:21:02.359 --> 00:21:06.439
So you can do the configuration changes by updating the Spark config.

00:21:07.239 --> 00:21:10.199
So you make a copy of that, and they make some of the changes.

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:15.479
So one of the things that I mentioned here is that for your user configuration,

00:21:15.479 --> 00:21:18.439
start small and just build slightly bigger.

00:21:18.439 --> 00:21:23.800
So I've seen some configurations, I'm going to say that I mean, these configurations,

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:27.319
that essentially look like, like this,

00:21:29.479 --> 00:21:32.760
like 20 lines before you even get to the connection.

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:38.199
It makes all sorts of changes, and it's making no sense of what is being requested.

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:44.599
So that is okay, if for whatever reason, that's what your environment needs.

00:21:44.599 --> 00:21:48.119
But if you're a new user that just trying to get some more,

00:21:49.479 --> 00:21:53.719
you know, performance out of your connection, try to start small, right?

00:21:54.359 --> 00:21:57.479
In this case, we'll just have executor memory,

00:21:57.479 --> 00:22:00.920
executor cores, instances, and the dynamic allocation,

00:22:01.640 --> 00:22:05.319
the same ones that are being proposed here in the article.

00:22:05.319 --> 00:22:09.560
So you can always go back to here, and I can connect.

00:22:10.359 --> 00:22:14.520
So notice that I'm going to connect here.

00:22:15.719 --> 00:22:18.920
And all I'm doing is I'm requesting one gigabyte per executor,

00:22:18.920 --> 00:22:21.800
one executor core, and give me 10 instances.

00:22:22.439 --> 00:22:27.640
So because I'm under my threshold, obviously, of the 32 gigabytes,

00:22:27.640 --> 00:22:31.400
I'm going to expect it to give me 10 instances,

00:22:31.400 --> 00:22:35.880
because I have definitely more than 10 cores,

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:40.199
and that's what I'm going to expect to see that return.

00:22:40.199 --> 00:22:46.199
So we go to Hue, I got one job running, job number 26.

00:22:52.599 --> 00:22:54.199
I think that's it, let's see.

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:55.719
There you go, 27.

00:23:01.640 --> 00:23:09.800
So I'm able to see this.

00:23:09.800 --> 00:23:15.160
So you'll notice that I got my 10 executors, right?

00:23:16.119 --> 00:23:23.560
And each one is giving me definitely like half of what I requested for the memory.

00:23:23.560 --> 00:23:29.400
That's because of the overhead that it's taking from my session,

00:23:29.400 --> 00:23:32.280
my requested session, and it's also...

00:23:35.400 --> 00:23:38.680
But it does give me all the executors that I asked for, right?

00:23:39.479 --> 00:23:40.760
So very important to see.

00:23:41.319 --> 00:23:49.239
Going back to the point about that one node can have multiple executors.

00:23:49.239 --> 00:23:50.439
So this is a worker node.

00:23:50.439 --> 00:23:56.359
See this, it has the same IP address, but it has two different ports, right?

00:23:56.359 --> 00:23:58.920
And these are the ports to the actual executor.

00:23:58.920 --> 00:24:03.079
So here you can see that there's two executors in the same machine.

00:24:03.079 --> 00:24:06.680
So they're going to act as if they were their own little like virtual machines,

00:24:06.680 --> 00:24:09.560
but they're really both inside the same box.

00:24:11.479 --> 00:24:18.520
This is important to also note that there is a balancing act that has to take place

00:24:18.520 --> 00:24:25.239
between how much resources you're giving each executor and how many executors you have.

00:24:25.239 --> 00:24:29.239
Because in this case, this is a very small cluster again.

00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:32.760
But when we talk about the larger clusters,

00:24:32.760 --> 00:24:38.920
the certain best practices that you need to approach it, you should use to approach it.

00:24:38.920 --> 00:24:43.079
So I would definitely recommend you going to this article.

00:24:43.079 --> 00:24:50.839
I have a link to a Nice Cloudera article where they discuss that

00:24:51.640 --> 00:24:56.280
and kind of explain how the resources are given

00:24:56.280 --> 00:24:58.839
and some of the best practices are talked about here.

00:24:58.839 --> 00:25:01.640
So I would definitely go back to that.

