00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:40.359
Another thing that I wanted to suggest is, like it mentions here,

00:26:40.359 --> 00:26:42.920
we need to give dynamic allocation a chance.

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:47.719
So dynamic allocation, and it's also mentioned in the article,

00:26:49.959 --> 00:26:55.640
it's a way that Yarn can give you the resources that you need on demand, right?

00:26:55.640 --> 00:27:00.040
So if you're working on a cluster that other people are using as well,

00:27:00.040 --> 00:27:02.280
then you may want to consider this.

00:27:02.280 --> 00:27:09.000
That way, Yarn can decide to add or remove resources for your Spark connection as needed.

00:27:09.640 --> 00:27:14.439
And all you have to do to get it is essentially don't put any configuration.

00:27:15.719 --> 00:27:18.199
This is native to a Yarn implementation.

