So maybe something that you want to consider looking at.

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:12.600
I just made a change recently for it to support older versions of Hive.

00:40:12.600 --> 00:40:16.439
So if you tried it before and it didn't work, just know that it does work now.

00:40:16.439 --> 00:40:24.840
I have a quick appendix down here that talks about creating a new Hive table,

00:40:24.840 --> 00:40:34.040
which is how I actually got the Hive metastore loaded with the flights table here.

00:40:35.080 --> 00:40:39.639
So something that we don't talk about much is this function right here.

00:40:39.639 --> 00:40:40.919
Spark write table.

00:40:40.919 --> 00:40:45.239
If you're working on a Spark and Hive cluster managed by Yarn,

00:40:47.080 --> 00:40:52.600
and if you want to persist data, because you know, as soon as I close my connection here,

00:40:52.600 --> 00:40:54.199
my data is gone, right?

00:40:54.199 --> 00:40:59.320
And I've had some folks ask questions about, okay, what if I want to keep the data?

00:40:59.320 --> 00:41:05.239
You know, usually you would like create a large file and put in HDFS and then something else

00:41:05.239 --> 00:41:05.800
with it.

00:41:05.800 --> 00:41:09.159
But normally what we want to do is to go back and analyze it later.

00:41:09.959 --> 00:41:18.679
You can do Spark write table and take the Spark data frame and then give it a name.

00:41:18.679 --> 00:41:20.840
And that's the name that ended up here.

00:41:21.479 --> 00:41:29.000
And what it does in the background, it creates not only the actual mapping and all that,

00:41:29.719 --> 00:41:31.639
but also does the partition for us.

00:41:32.360 --> 00:41:38.520
So it creates a bunch of smaller parquet files and saves them into the warehouse folder.

00:41:38.520 --> 00:41:41.320
So a really nice function.

00:41:41.320 --> 00:41:45.399
I don't think we talked about it too much, but if you're in a Yarn environment, this would

00:41:45.399 --> 00:41:47.080
definitely be of advantage.

00:41:49.320 --> 00:41:52.280
So I'll show you, this is the standalone cluster.

00:41:53.560 --> 00:41:56.840
So I did the same thing and this was going to be part of the original

00:41:59.639 --> 00:42:00.139
demo.

00:42:00.760 --> 00:42:04.600
But I do want to show you real quick here, the standalone cluster.

00:42:05.239 --> 00:42:07.000
And if I were to do a connection here.

00:42:15.800 --> 00:42:23.959
So I'm going to, in a Spark standalone, to go to the actual location, which your job

00:42:23.959 --> 00:42:26.919
is, because there's only one job from the driver.

00:42:26.919 --> 00:42:33.000
You can just switch from the same URL, but to port 8088.

00:42:33.560 --> 00:42:35.719
Oh, excuse me, port 40.

00:42:35.719 --> 00:42:36.520
Sorry, port 40.

00:42:37.879 --> 00:42:40.360
And that will show you here all the jobs.

00:42:40.360 --> 00:42:42.439
And I can show you here the executor page.

00:42:44.360 --> 00:42:53.239
Something about the executor page is that the course will always be managed by the master

00:42:53.239 --> 00:42:57.800
and will always be regarding how many actual servers you have.

00:42:58.520 --> 00:43:02.120
So it's very rare when we're going to need more than one

00:43:06.360 --> 00:43:08.120
executor per node.

00:43:08.120 --> 00:43:14.840
And it's kind of hard to set it up unless you start manipulating the dynamic allocation

00:43:14.840 --> 00:43:22.199
and the number of course to be lower than what's available in the server, in the worker

00:43:22.199 --> 00:43:23.000
node.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:27.320
So again, you'll notice that all these are the same except the memory fraction.

00:43:27.399 --> 00:43:29.320
You actually have control over that.

00:43:29.320 --> 00:43:31.959
So I'm going to close this real quick and reopen it.

00:43:33.479 --> 00:43:37.800
So memory fraction will actually give me closer to the seven gigabytes because I'm setting

00:43:37.800 --> 00:43:39.080
it to 90%.

00:43:40.760 --> 00:43:50.199
And if I go back here, so you see it gives me 35 gigabytes, which is the, I said, give

00:43:50.199 --> 00:43:50.760
me two.

00:43:51.639 --> 00:43:53.239
So I'm going to reopen it here.

00:43:53.800 --> 00:44:00.040
And I'm going to say, yeah, 90%, what I'm asking for.

00:44:00.040 --> 00:44:02.600
So if I were to change this to 30%, for example.

00:44:11.320 --> 00:44:13.080
And then push here.

00:44:14.840 --> 00:44:16.439
And you notice that now it's much slower.

00:44:17.719 --> 00:44:21.080
And that's because the fraction is something that you can control.

00:44:21.080 --> 00:44:26.520
It's a big point that if you're going to be doing some standalone, it's also mentioned

00:44:26.520 --> 00:44:32.360
in the article, consider moving the memory fraction a little bit too, if you need more

00:44:33.159 --> 00:44:34.679
space in your cluster.

00:44:36.679 --> 00:44:41.800
So just to kind of do a quick review, I'm going to go back to here.

00:44:41.800 --> 00:44:46.360
If you have, this is to me the key item for today.

00:44:46.760 --> 00:44:51.639
If you had data load options and questions, definitely think about these two options,

00:44:51.639 --> 00:44:52.199
right?

00:44:52.199 --> 00:44:56.760
And always try to load the data from the remote source directly into Spark.

00:44:58.520 --> 00:45:04.439
And always consider the option to be more of a, just for smaller tables, as well as

00:45:04.439 --> 00:45:10.840
a last resort if you don't, not all of the nodes have access to the same data source.

00:45:12.280 --> 00:45:13.719
Okay, so that's all I have.

00:45:13.719 --> 00:45:14.360
And thank you.

